👉 Steps happening internally:

1️ Object obj is created
2️ Java allocates memory for object
3️ logic() method is accessed using the object
4️ Parameters a and b are passed
5️ Returned value stored in temp


👉 Why we removed static from the method

1. Static Method

(i) Belongs to the class
(ii)Can be called without creating an object

Example : static int logic(int a, int b)
Calling : logic(a,b);

2. Non-Static Method (Instance Method)

(i) Belongs to the object of the class
(ii)Requires an object to call it

Example : int logic(int a, int b)
Calling : obj.logic(a,b);

👉 Why object is required here

Since we removed static, the method logic() now belongs to the instance of the class, not the class itself.
Therefore Java requires an object to access it.

👉 Throughout the object creation :

The values from the method call (a and b) are copied to the a and b of the function logic. Thus even if we modify the values of a and b
inside the method, the values in the main method will not change.

