👉 Void return type 

In Java, void means the method does not return any value.
When a method is declared with void, it performs some task but does not send any result back to the caller.

Syntax is same as we used earlier for creation of Methods.

Example program for using void return type with object creation

import java.util.Scanner;
public class Methods{
    void methods(int a , int b){
        if(a>b){
            System.out.println("Entered number : "+a+" is greater than "+b);
        }
        else{
            System.out.println("Entered number : "+a+" is lesser than "+b);
        }
    }
    public static void main(String[] args){
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Enter the values of a and b respectively : ");
        int a = sc.nextInt();
        int b = sc.nextInt();
        Methods obj = new Methods();
        obj.methods(a,b);
    }
}

Output :

Enter the values of a and b respectively : 
4
5
Entered number : 4 is lesser than 5
